body:
It seems like calling `super` in the child class is only supported in `new`.

Calling `super` in the `new` function works:

```
program main;

    class object;
        function new();
            $display("object");
        endfunction
    endclass

    class test extends object;
        function new();
            super.new();
            $display("test");
        endfunction
    endclass

    object obj;
    test tst;

    initial begin
        obj = new();
        tst = new();
    end 

endprogram
```

Output:

```
iverilog -o test -g2012 test.sv
vvp test
object
object
test
```

Adding two new functions also works:

```
program main;

    class object;
        function new();
            $display("object");
        endfunction
        
        function void print();
            $display("object: print");
        endfunction
    endclass

    class test extends object;
        function new();
            super.new();
            $display("test");
        endfunction
        
        function void print();
            $display("test: print");
        endfunction
    endclass

    object obj;
    test tst;

    initial begin
        obj = new();
        obj.print();
        tst = new();
        tst.print();
    end 

endprogram
```

Output:

```
iverilog -o test -g2012 test.sv
vvp test
object
object: print
object
test
test: print
```

But calling `super` in the print function of the child gives the following:

```
program main;

    class object;
        function new();
            $display("object");
        endfunction
        
        function void print();
            $display("object: print");
        endfunction
    endclass

    class test extends object;
        function new();
            super.new();
            $display("test");
        endfunction
        
        function void print();
            super.print();
            $display("test: print");
        endfunction
    endclass

    object obj;
    test tst;

    initial begin
        obj = new();
        obj.print();
        tst = new();
        tst.print();
    end 

endprogram
```

Output:

```
iverilog -o test -g2012 test.sv
iverilog_test.sv:20: sorry: Implicit class handle "super" not supported.
iverilog_test.sv:20: error: Enable of unknown task ``#.print''.
1 error(s) during elaboration.
```

I haven't seen an issue yet concerning this, that's why I have created this one.

